---
import MarketingLayout from "../../components/marketing/MarketingLayout.astro";

const title = "Authorization Sprawl with FraiseQL";
const description = "Consolidate authorization logic at the database level. Stop scattering RBAC across resolvers.";
---

<MarketingLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <section class="use-case-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Authorization: One Source of Truth</h1>
      <p>Stop scattering RBAC across 47 field resolvers. Move authorization to the database.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="use-case-content">
    <div class="container">

      <section class="problem-section">
        <h2>The Authorization Sprawl Problem</h2>

        <p>In traditional GraphQL, authorization logic is scattered everywhere:</p>

        <div class="problem-example">
          <h3>Typical Authorization Mess</h3>
          <pre><code set:html={`# Authorization in resolver 1
@resolver
async def user(info, id: str) -> User:
  if not info.context["user"].can_view(id):  # Check 1
    raise PermissionError()
  return db.find_user(id)

# Authorization in resolver 2
@resolver
async def posts(parent: User, info) -> list[Post]:
  if not info.context["user"].can_view_posts(parent.id):  # Check 2
    raise PermissionError()
  return db.find_posts(parent.id)

# Authorization in resolver 3
@resolver
async def comments(parent: Post, info) -> list[Comment]:
  if not info.context["user"].can_view_comments(parent.id):  # Check 3
    raise PermissionError()
  return db.find_comments(parent.id)

# By resolver 47, you've written 47 different authorization checks
# Some check roles, some check ownership, some check teams
# Consistency: ❌ ZERO`}></code></pre>
        </div>

        <div class="risk-grid">
          <div class="risk-item">
            <h4>🔓 Authorization Bypass</h4>
            <p>Forget one check and data leaks</p>
          </div>
          <div class="risk-item">
            <h4>🔀 Inconsistent Rules</h4>
            <p>Same user, different permissions in different resolvers</p>
          </div>
          <div class="risk-item">
            <h4>🐛 Hard to Audit</h4>
            <p>Where is authorization actually enforced?</p>
          </div>
          <div class="risk-item">
            <h4>😰 Maintenance Nightmare</h4>
            <p>Change a permission rule = update 20+ resolvers</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="solution-section">
        <h2>FraiseQL Solution: Database-Level Authorization</h2>

        <p>Define authorization once in SQL views. Every query respects it automatically.</p>

        <div class="solution-step">
          <h3>Step 1: Consolidate Authorization in Views</h3>
          <pre><code set:html={`-- Single source of truth for all authorization
CREATE VIEW v_user_visible_posts AS
SELECT
  jsonb_build_object(
    'id', p.id::text,
    'title', p.title,
    'content', p.content,
    'author_id', p.author_id::text,
    'created_at', p.created_at
  ) AS data
FROM tb_post p
WHERE
  -- Public posts anyone can see
  p.is_public = true
  OR
  -- Posts user authored
  p.author_id = current_setting('app.user_id')::uuid
  OR
  -- Posts in teams user belongs to
  EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM tb_team_member tm
    WHERE tm.team_id = p.team_id
      AND tm.user_id = current_setting('app.user_id')::uuid
  );`}></code></pre>
        </div>

        <div class="solution-step">
          <h3>Step 2: Set Context Once</h3>
          <pre><code set:html={`# Single authorization check at the API level
@fraiseql.query(sql_source="v_user_visible_posts")
def posts() -> list[Post]:
  # User context is set by the Rust runtime via fraiseql.toml
  # All views respect this context automatically
  pass`}></code></pre>
        </div>

        <div class="solution-step">
          <h3>Step 3: No Per-Field Checks Needed</h3>
          <pre><code set:html={`@fraiseql.type
class Post:
  id: UUID
  title: str
  content: str
  author_id: UUID
  created_at: str

# No resolver checks needed
# The view already enforces authorization`}></code></pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="example-section">
        <h2>Real-World: Multi-Team SaaS</h2>

        <div class="example-box">
          <h3>Authorization Rules:</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Users see only their own team's data</li>
            <li>Admins see all data</li>
            <li>Editors can modify posts, viewers are read-only</li>
            <li>Team leads see their team + team leads' reports</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>FraiseQL Approach: Single View</h3>
          <pre><code set:html={`CREATE VIEW v_accessible_posts AS
SELECT
  jsonb_build_object(
    'id', p.id::text,
    'title', p.title,
    'can_edit', CASE
      WHEN current_setting('app.user_role') = 'admin' THEN true
      WHEN current_setting('app.user_role') = 'editor'
        AND tm.user_id IS NOT NULL THEN true
      ELSE false
    END,
    'team', jsonb_build_object(
      'id', t.id::text,
      'name', t.name
    )
  ) AS data
FROM tb_post p
JOIN tb_team t ON p.team_id = t.id
LEFT JOIN tb_team_member tm ON (
  t.id = tm.team_id
  AND tm.user_id = current_setting('app.user_id')::uuid
)
WHERE
  -- Admins see everything
  current_setting('app.user_role') = 'admin'
  OR
  -- Regular users see only their team
  (
    EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM tb_team_member
      WHERE team_id = p.team_id
        AND user_id = current_setting('app.user_id')::uuid
    )
  )
  OR
  -- Team leads see peer team leads
  (
    current_setting('app.user_role') = 'team_lead'
    AND EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM tb_team_member tl
      WHERE tl.user_id = current_setting('app.user_id')::uuid
        AND tl.role = 'team_lead'
        AND tl.team_id IN (
          SELECT team_id FROM tb_team_member
          WHERE user_id = p.author_id
        )
    )
  );`}></code></pre>

          <p><strong>Result:</strong> Authorization is tested once, applies everywhere.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="patterns-section">
        <h2>Authorization Patterns</h2>

        <div class="pattern-box">
          <h3>Pattern 1: Role-Based Access Control</h3>
          <pre><code set:html={`CREATE VIEW v_rbac_posts AS
SELECT ... FROM tb_post p
WHERE (
  current_setting('app.user_role') = 'admin'
) OR (
  current_setting('app.user_role') = 'editor'
  AND p.author_id = current_setting('app.user_id')::uuid
) OR (
  current_setting('app.user_role') = 'viewer'
  AND p.is_published = true
);`}></code></pre>
        </div>

        <div class="pattern-box">
          <h3>Pattern 2: Ownership-Based</h3>
          <pre><code set:html={`CREATE VIEW v_owned_resources AS
SELECT ... FROM tb_resource r
WHERE r.owner_id = current_setting('app.user_id')::uuid
  OR r.org_id IN (
    SELECT org_id FROM tb_org_member
    WHERE user_id = current_setting('app.user_id')::uuid
  );`}></code></pre>
        </div>

        <div class="pattern-box">
          <h3>Pattern 3: Hierarchical Permissions</h3>
          <pre><code set:html={`CREATE VIEW v_hierarchical_access AS
SELECT ... FROM tb_resource r
WHERE r.org_id = current_setting('app.org_id')::uuid
  AND (
    -- Can access own resources
    r.created_by = current_setting('app.user_id')::uuid
    OR
    -- Can access team resources if team lead
    (
      r.team_id = current_setting('app.team_id')::uuid
      AND current_setting('app.user_role') = 'team_lead'
    )
    OR
    -- Can access org resources if admin
    (
      current_setting('app.user_role') = 'admin'
    )
  );`}></code></pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="testing-section">
        <h2>Testing Authorization</h2>

        <div class="testing-box">
          <h3>Test Cases Are Simpler</h3>
          <pre><code set:html={`# Test: User can't see other team's data
def test_user_isolation():
  # Set context for Team A user
  db.execute("SET app.user_id = 'team-a-user'")
  posts_team_a = db.find_many("v_accessible_posts")

  # Set context for Team B user
  db.execute("SET app.user_id = 'team-b-user'")
  posts_team_b = db.find_many("v_accessible_posts")

  # They see different data
  assert posts_team_a[0]["team_id"] != posts_team_b[0]["team_id"]

# You're not testing resolver logic
# You're testing the database view behavior
# Much simpler and more reliable`}></code></pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="benefits-section">
        <h2>Authorization Benefits</h2>

        <div class="benefit-grid">
          <div class="benefit-card">
            <h3>✅ Single Source of Truth</h3>
            <p>One place to define and audit authorization.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="benefit-card">
            <h3>✅ No Bypass Possible</h3>
            <p>Database enforces rules for every query, automatically.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="benefit-card">
            <h3>✅ Easy to Audit</h3>
            <p>SQL views are readable. Compliance teams understand them.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="benefit-card">
            <h3>✅ Change Once, Apply Everywhere</h3>
            <p>Update the view, all queries respect new rules.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="benefit-card">
            <h3>✅ Testable Rules</h3>
            <p>Test authorization logic like SQL, not resolver mocking.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="benefit-card">
            <h3>✅ Performance</h3>
            <p>Database optimizes authorization filters.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="related-section">
        <h2>Related Use Cases</h2>
        <div class="related-grid">
          <div class="related-box">
            <h3>⚖️ Regulated Industries</h3>
            <p>Authorization + compliance in one place.</p>
            <a href="/use-cases/regulated-industries/" class="link">Read →</a>
          </div>
          <div class="related-box">
            <h3>🏢 Enterprise SaaS</h3>
            <p>Multi-tenant isolation with database-level RBAC.</p>
            <a href="/use-cases/enterprise-saas/" class="link">Read →</a>
          </div>
          <div class="related-box">
            <h3>🔒 SQL Ownership</h3>
            <p>Own your queries, own your security.</p>
            <a href="/docs/concepts/how-it-works/" class="link">Read →</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="cta-section">
        <h2>Eliminate Authorization Sprawl</h2>
        <p>Build secure systems with clear, auditable authorization logic.</p>
        <div class="cta-buttons">
          <a href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/" class="btn btn-primary">Get Started</a>
          <a href="/use-cases/" class="btn btn-secondary">← Back to Use Cases</a>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>
  </section>

</MarketingLayout>

<style>
  .use-case-hero {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--fraise-500) 0%, var(--fraise-600) 100%);
    color: white;
    padding: var(--spacing-16) var(--spacing-6);
    text-align: center;
  }

  .use-case-hero h1 {
    font-size: 2.5rem;
    margin: 0 0 var(--spacing-3) 0;
    font-weight: 700;
  }

